[[File:ALEX JOHNSTON (15568284310).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Johnson at the [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations]]]]
'''Alex Johnston''' (born 14 January 1995) is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|fb}} and {{rlp|wg}}er for the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. He won the [[2014 NRL Grand Final|2014 NRL Premiership]] with the Rabbitohs.

==Background==
Born in [[Sydney|Sydney, New South Wales]], Johnston is of [[Indigenous Australians|Indigenous Australian]] and [[Papua New Guinean]] descent. He played his junior rugby league for  [[La Perouse United]] and attended Endeavour Sports High School (where he completed the [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|HSC]]) before being signed by the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]]. As a youngster, Johnston played for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] Under 16s and 18s teams and [[Australian Schoolboys rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]] team. In 2013, Johnston played for the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]]' [[S. G. Ball Cup]] and [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] teams before moving on to the Rabbitohs' [[New South Wales Cup]] team, [[North Sydney Bears]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rleague.com/players/Alex-Johnston_4052/Stats/|accessdate=25 April 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426235830/http://rleague.com/players/Alex-Johnston_4052/Stats/|archivedate=26 April 2014 |title=Alex Johnson player results, scores, news and statistics}}</ref>

==Playing career==

===2014===
In Round 8 of the [[2014 NRL season]], Johnston was selected to make his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] over dumped Rabbitohs winger [[Nathan Merritt]] against the [[Brisbane Broncos]] on the {{rlp|wg}}, scoring a try in the 28-26 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]] on Anzac Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/south-sydney-star-greg-inglis-scores-brilliant-solo-try-in-controversial-win/story-fni3fbgz-1226896075641|title=South Sydney Star Greg Inglis Scores Brilliant Solo Try in Controversial Win|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> He continued to perform on both the left and right wing throughout the year. At times, Johnston was referred to as the successor of [[Greg Inglis]], for his ability to play fullback as well as wing. In Round 21, Johnston scored his first ever hat-trick against the [[Newcastle Knights]] in the Rabbitohs 50-10 victory. On 5 October 2014, in the Rabbitohs [[2014 NRL Grand Final]] match against the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], Johnston played on the wing and scored the first try of the match to lead the South Sydney Rabbitohs 30-6 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/south-sydney-rabbitohs-win-2014-nrl-grand-final-defeating-canterbury-bulldogs-306/story-fni3fbgz-1227080755667|title=South Sydney Rabbitohs Win 2014 Grand final Defeating Canterbury Bulldogs|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/rabbitohs-grand-final-player-ratings/tabid/10874/newsid/82375/default.aspx|title=Rabbitohs Grand Final Player Ratings|publisher=NRL.com|date=2014-10-05|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> Johnston finished his brilliant debut year in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]] as being the competitions highest tryscorer of the 2014 NRL season with 21 tries in 18 matches. In September 2014, it was revealed that the [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team]] were attempting to have Johnston pledge his allegiance to [[Papua New Guinea]] as his grandmother is from a village in Lumi, a place in the West Sepik Province of Papua New Guinea.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.triplem.com.au/sydney/sport/nrl/news/2014/9/rabbitohs-star-alex-johnston-pngs-no1-target-/|title=Rabbitohs Star Alex Johnston PNG's No.1 Target &#124; Triple M NRL|publisher=Triplem.com.au|date=2014-09-07|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> On 14 October 2014, Johnston was selected for the [[Australia Kangaroos]] [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations|2014 Four Nations]] squad but didn't make an appearance in any of Australia's four matches.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Carayannis|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/south-sydney-rabbitohs/south-sydney-rabbitohs-dylan-walker-and-alex-johnston-selected-for-kangaroos-20141014-115yws.html|title=South Sydney Rabbitohs Dylan Walker and Alex Johnston selected for Kangaroos|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref>

===2015===
On 13 February 2015, Johnston played on the wing for the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] against the [[NRL All Stars team|NRL All Stars]] in the [[2015 All Stars match]] at [[Robina Stadium|Cbus Super Stadium]], the Indigenous side winning 20-6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/the-indigenous-all-stars-have-beaten-the-nrl-stars-20-6-at-cbus-stadium/story-fni3fbgz-1227219053165|title=Indigenous All Stars Have Beaten the NRL All Stars 20-6|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> On 23 February, he played for the Rabbitohs in the [[2015 World Club Series|2015 World Club Challenge]] match against [[2014 Super League Grand Final]] premiers [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]], playing on the wing in the Rabbitohs' 39-0 win at [[Langtree Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/world-club-challenge-south-sydney-rabbitohs-thrash-st-helens-saints-to-complete-aussie-series-sweep/story-e6frf3uu-1227234753346|title=South Sydney Thrash St Helens|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> For the [[2015 Anzac Test]], he was selected to make his debut for [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia]] against [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]], playing on the wing in the Kangaroos' 12-26 loss at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/representative-round-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/85557/default.aspx|title=Representative Round team lists|publisher=NRL.com|date=2015-04-28|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/anzac-test-new-zealands-comprehensive-defeat-of-australia-could-spell-the-end-for-coach-tim-sheens-and-several-veterans/story-fnp0lyn6-1227332702787|title=New Zealnd's Comprehensive Defeat of Australia Could Spell the End for Coach Tim Sheens and Several Veterans|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-13}}</ref> On 13 May, he re-signed with the Rabbitohs on a 2-year contract to the end of the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.rabbitohs.com.au/news/2015/05/13/rabbitohs_extend_con1.html|title=Extend Contracts of Alex Johnston and Cameron McInnes Until End of 2017|publisher=Rabbitohs.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Carayannis|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/south-sydney-rabbitohs/south-sydney-rabbitohs-resign-alex-johnston-and-cameron-mcinnes-20150513-gh0f66.html|title=South Sydney Rabbitohs re-sign Alex Johnston and Cameron McInnes|website=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref> On 8 July, he was selected to be 18th man for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] team for Game 3 of the [[2015 State of Origin series]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Carayannis|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/south-sydney-rabbitohs/state-of-origin-south-sydney-duo-alex-johnston-and-dylan-walker-on-verge-of-nsw-call-up-for-origin-ii-20150610-ghkkc8.html|title=State of Origin: South Sydney duo Alex Johnston and Dylan Walker on verge of NSW call up for Origin II|website=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref> He finished off the [[2015 NRL season|2015 season]] as the Rabbitohs' highest try-scorer with 17 tries in 25 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTItMTY2MC00LS0tLS0tMjA4MDItLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=2015-10-29|accessdate=2015-12-26}}</ref> On 26 September, he played for the [[Prime Minister's XIII]] against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], playing on the wing and scoring a try in his team's 40-12 win at [[Port Moresby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/merrin-to-lead-prime-ministers-xiii/tabid/10874/newsid/89831/default.aspx|title=Merrin to lead Prime Minister's XIII|website=NRL.com|date=2015-09-15|accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Decent|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/australian-prime-ministers-xiii-beat-papua-new-guinea-4012-in-port-moresby-20150926-gjvoj6.html|title=Australian Prime Minister's XIII beat Papua New Guinea 40-12 in Port Moresby|website=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref> On 15 December, he was named on the wing for the Indigenous All Stars team to play the [[NRL All Stars team|World All Stars]] on 13 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/teams-named-for-nrl-all-stars-match/tabid/10874/newsid/91188/default.aspx|title=Teams named for NRL All Stars match|website=NRL.com|date=2015-12-15|accessdate=2015-12-21}}</ref>

===2016===
On 13 January, Johnston was named in the emerging [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales Blues]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/daley-names-2016-emerging-blues/tabid/10874/newsid/91337/default.aspx|title=Daley names 2016 Emerging Blues|website=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-01-15}}</ref> In February, he played for the Rabbitohs in the [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]], scoring the opening try of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/rabbitohs-name-2016-nines-squad/|title=Rabbitohs name 2016 Nines squad|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=|accessdate=2016-02-04|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204205430/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/rabbitohs-name-2016-nines-squad/|archivedate=4 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was selected on the wing and scored four tries in the Rabbitohs' first three matches of the season before suffering a hamstring injury that saw him sit out for several weeks. In his return game in Round 10 against the [[Parramatta Eels]], he played in his preferred position at fullback in the Rabbitohs' 22-20 win. He was renamed in the fullback position in Round 15, once again against the Eels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTItMTY3Ny00LS0tLS0tMjA4MDItLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2016-06-17}}</ref> He was then moved back and forth as the Rabbitohs attempted to find a line-up that would win them. In Round 23, Johnston played on the wing when the Rabbitohs broke their nine-game losing streak with a 41-22 win over the [[New Zealand Warriors]]. He played their for the next three final games which were all won by South Sydney. Johnston finished the 2016 season with 11 tries from 18 matches

=== 2017 ===
In Round One of the 2017 season, South Sydney fullback, Greg Inglis suffered what was deemed to be a season-ending injury to his ACL in the Rabbitohs 18-34 defeat against the [[Wests Tigers]]. In Round 2, Johnston was named at fullback for the Rabbitohs clash with the [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly Sea Eagles]]. Johnston scored two tries in the position in his sides' 18-38 win at [[Brookvale Oval]].  On June 14, he re-signed with the Rabbitohs until the end of the 2020 season. On July 2 he scored 5 tries against the Penrith Panthers to be the first Rabbitohs player since Nathan Merritt in 2011 to achieve 5 tries in a match. In round 21, Alex Johnston was switched back to fullback after poor performances by Souths who were on a three game losing streak. He scored an amazing try in the Rabbitohs' 32 - 18 loss against the Raiders. He then went on to score 6 tries in his next 3 games and was the leading try scorer with 2 rounds to go. However, against the New Zealand Warriors in Round 24, Johnston injured his hamstring as he was scoring a try in the 36 - 18 win. He was ruled out for the rest of the season, with the Rabbitohs losing their last 2 matches. Johnston finished season 2017 with him playing 22 matches and scoring 22 tries, the second highest tryscorer that year.

=== 2018 ===
Johnston was part of the South Sydney side which returned to form in 2018 finishing 3rd on the table at the end of the regular season.  Johnston made 24 appearances for Souths scoring 8 tries as the club finished one game short of the grand final losing to Eastern Suburbs 12-4.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/09/22/player-ratings-roosters-v-rabbitohs/</ref><ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTItMTcxNy00LS0tLS0tMjA4MDItLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t</ref>

